the obsession i have for pushing boundaries in fashion goes back to the times of having single digit candles on my birthday cake (although it was definitely a lot more poly satin and cheap feather boas back then). for the past 3 years, my life has been consumed with activewear. i can’t even begin to describe how thankful i am to find this love for activewear design. while active is now and will always be embedded in the brand dna (and will continue to drop with new styles regularly all year every year forever), im excited to explore the marriage of my first love (ready-to-wear) and my new love (activewear). a story of the two styles merged into one very playful, edgy, sporty, and colorful concept: ba sport rtw coming fall 2023 🦋

spare your cliche “iTs NoT mOdEsT” today. i refuse to let anyone steal my joy on the internet. this challenge was clearly given to us with the brief of being creative with the way we moved forward with our duality words. i didn’t want to take it literally and do front/back, right/left, top/bottom. i wanted to create something with an abstract approach. the style of the dress is modest IF you wanted to make it in an opaque fabric. in another fabric, it would be full coverage, but instead of an opaque fabric, i used sheer lace which made it sexy. fashion is subjective and all of us were never meant to meet the brief with the exact same approach. it’s my way of doing the challenge and just because it’s not how YOU would have approached it doesn’t mean it wasn’t the right one. i’m really proud of this look and the construction that went into lining up all the stripes, adding the lace selvage, and making sure that corset bodysuit was dyed and cut to perfection so it didn’t fall down when @luzzlopezz walked down the runway. use your imagination yall, it’s exhilarating when you don’t have such a closed mind towards fashion 💋
and then there were 5 🦋

obsessed with my sporty stripe take on menswear red carpet eleganza - and i’d do it again the same ✨ @keenan.png killed this look on the runway! the cuffs on the sleeves are so intricately detailed, the stripes are matching for the second week in a row, and the pants are a signature style, but i changed them up to have hardware on the outside with only a slight ankle flare instead of a thigh high slit option. menswear, but still make it BA! what you didn’t see is the peeps of baby blue polka dot charmeuse lining for the pockets - always something sweet and surprising just for my customers! thank you @kingofbingo for seeing my vision and the continued support - pants and top are being sewn for you as we speak!

we were bound and determined to start the show off hella strong. a stunning bra and culotte set inspired by the utilitarian side of sport. in the active market, we tend to hide the storage, the cargo, the pockets inside the spandex uniform. instead, this look exposed the features that allow us to haul our belongings and make us look like we have our sh!t together. the styling was strategic - we made all the socks in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear while also being a look that can be versatile for an evening outing.

this was a true “trust-the-process” full look. we played with all avenues of active. but i wanted to push it further. taking the placket and applying it to the skirt gives it an upscale feel with the striped corset, but the leggings and top bring it back to a gym mood being in the large eye mesh. again, we made all the socks in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear. the stripes on the corset were labors of love - we cut the stripes from the striped organza, passed the organza edges so only the stripe was exposed, and top stitched the stripes to the corset casing.
•
shoutout to @notequal for helping with me a second pair of eyes on this one. fabio truly came through to show me each avenue we could travel to bring this look together!

i knew i wanted to cut a full circle dress to bring some MOVEMENT to the runway. we brought in the plackets with snaps to stamp on the dna pretty heavy. print is my love language so this is where she got to shine but with so much volume that you wouldn’t be able to look away. the biker shorts just nod to the activewear we do so well and keep the dress grounded in a way that is on brand. the publications may think the mix of color and polka-dots is tacky, but if it’s not over the top, i don’t want it. again, we made all the socks in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear.

a true nod to what we do best. this look needs very little explanation. i wanted this look to be in the middle, to keep the collection grounded and rooted, and to show appreciation/growth of how far we have come from just starting to chisel our place in the active market. i will give us more credit than normal - we had hardly any activewear machinery to make this spandex look, yet we made it work anyhow. chartreuse is everything and stripes bring in the color palette. we took our mesh top and extended the sleeve to floor length so the scrunching gave it some dimension.

an actual RTW goddess. it all starts here - this shirt dress is made of the striped organza and shows the versatility of this textile because here on out, it gets manipulated as a trim. the look is 4 pieces with the strappy bralette staple, the biker short in a power mesh for transparency, and then a sporty skirt number that is nodding to workout couture for either the gym or an outing. we really had to figure out the perfect styling for the shirt dress or it wouldn’t work. the dimension and details of the dress were everything with the mix of textile and trim. truly can’t wait to show you how intricate the waist to back contraption is - it’s wild. again, we made all the socks in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear.

shoutout to @notequal yet again for playing with proportions here and listening to my vision while also keeping me open to different possibilities. this collection wouldn’t have happened if it wasn’t for you, babe.

the pants that have shaken you all to your core. this pant textile was a flat gray and black geometric fabric. there were no lines along the sides of the shapes. we all cut strips on strips on strips (like hundreds to cover these and the finale dress), pressed the organza edges to the back, and top stitched them to the edges of the lines in the shapes. SO MUCH WORK went into these pants and i suggest you zoom in to give it a look. the top is our iconic half top with ribbing to make it cohesive, and finally the most strapped top ever to grace the runway. this one could be tied a million different ways. again, we made all the socks in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear.

the perfect closer for a killer collection. mimi, thank you for OWNING the runway in this piece. you brought me and my collection to LIFE. when it comes to the look, it speaks for itself. this gown fabric was the same as the pant - the textile was a flat gray and black geometric fabric. there were no lines along the sides of the shapes. we all cut strips on strips on strips (like hundreds to cover these and the finale dress), pressed the organza edges to the back, and top stitched them to the edges of the lines in the shapes. our plackets in the front made this piece super versatile depending how much slit the person would want to show. again, we made all the socks AND mimi’s gloves in the collection with power mesh and knit ribbing, and the hardware brings this look to a luxury level of activewear.
